<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910522-0035</DOCNO><DOCID>910522-0035.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Atari Games Corp.:   Judge Grants Stay to Firm   In Nintendo's Copyright Suit</HL><DATE>05/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9</SO><CO>   J.NTD</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>JAPAN (JA)</RE><LP>   Atari Games Corp., San Francisco, won a small reprieve ina copyright-infringement case brought against it by Nintendoof America Inc.   A federal judge granted Atari Games a stay of aninjunction issued March 27 that ordered it to stop marketingcartridges that use Nintendo's computer program, the twocompanies said. The stay lets Atari Games, Milpitas, Calif.,and its subsidiary, Tengen Inc., continue to manufacture andmarket its Nintendo-compatible game cartridges for six monthsor until the matter is heard on appeal.</LP><TEXT>   The stay, issued in San Francisco, is the latest chapterin more than two years of litigation between the two gamemakers. Closely held Atari Games sued the Redmond,Wash.-based unit of Japan's Nintendo Co. in 1988, chargingthe Japanese concern unfairly monopolized the U.S. home videogame market. The suit seeks for $100 million in trebledamages. Nintendo counter-sued, charging that Atari violatedits patents and other rights.   Nintendo said that, despite the stay, the judge&quot;reaffirmed the court's earlier decision that Tengen hadviolated Nintendo's intellectual property rights.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>